javaScript improves the user experience of the web page by converting a static page into an interactive one.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Values & variables 

var (old, function-scoped)
let (block-scoped, preferred for mutable variables)
const (block-scoped, for constants)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DataType

1. Primitive Data Types
These hold single values and are immutable.
 
Data Type           Example	                      Description
String	            "Hello"	                         Textual data
Number	             42, 3.14	                     Integers and floating-point numbers
Boolean	             true, false	                 Logical true or false
Null	             null	                         Represents an empty or unknown value
Undefined	         undefined	                     Variable declared but not assigned yet
Symbol	             Symbol("id")	                 Unique identifiers (ES6+)
BigInt	             12345678901234567890n	         Large integers (ES11 / ES2020+)


let name = "Alice";        // String
let age = 25;              // Number
let isActive = true;       // Boolean
let salary = null;         // Null
let city;                  // Undefined
const id = Symbol("id");   // Symbol
const bigNum = 9007199254740991n; // BigInt


2. Non-Primitive (Object) Data Types
These are complex types that can hold collections of values.

Type	         Example	                  Description
Object	      {name: "John", age: 30}	       Key-value pairs
Array	      [1, 2, 3, 4]	                   Ordered list of values
Function	  function greet() {}	           Reusable block of code
Date	      new Date()	                   Represents date and time
RegExp	      /abc/	                           Regular expression


let person = { name: "Alice", age: 25 }; // Object
let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];              // Array

function greet() {                       // Function
  console.log("Hello!");
}             
                          
let today = new Date();                 // Date object

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Operators

Assignment Operators
=	+=	-=	*=	/=	 %=

Arithmetic Operators 
+	-	*	/	%	-- 

Comparison Operators
==	===	!=	!==	><	>=	<=

Logical Operators
&&  `  !

String Operator
+

Conditional (Ternary) Operator
condition ? val1 : val2

